"""
Tier 2 -- All GDP Components' Response to Tier 1 Shocks (standalone)
================================================================

Does NOT re-run Tier 1. Reads the cleaned shock series Tier 1 already
saved to CSV, and pairs each shock against every Tier 2 GDP-component
proxy in its own small bivariate VAR.

Every proxy is tagged with which GDP accounting identity bucket it
belongs to (gdp_category) and its sign (+1 normally, -1 for Imports,
since Net Exports = Exports - Imports). This is what lets Tier 3 later
apply BEA weights correctly -- and it's also what stops you from
double-counting when a category has more than one proxy (e.g.
Investment has two: Capital Goods Orders and Durable Goods Orders).

GDP identity buckets covered here (Higgins 2014 / GDPNow-style split):
    PCE          -- Personal Consumption Expenditures
    Investment   -- Capital Goods Orders, Durable Goods Orders, Housing Starts
    Government   -- Public Construction Spending
    NetExports   -- Exports (+1), Imports (-1)
    Inventories  -- Wholesale/Business Inventories

WORKFLOW
--------
1. Load tier1_shocks.csv (already-cleaned/orthogonalized shocks)
2. Load every Tier 2 proxy
3. For every (shock, proxy) pair: fit a 2-variable VAR (shock first),
   run stability + whiteness diagnostics, extract the peak response
4. Print one summary table covering every pair, tagged by gdp_category
   and sign -- ready for Tier 3 to consume directly
5. Print a pooled-by-category preview: for categories with more than
   one proxy (Investment, NetExports), shows the sign-adjusted average
   response so you can see what Tier 3's aggregation will actually use
6. Interactive scenario test + on-demand plotting, same as before
7. Optional out-of-sample RMSE check for any single pair you want to
   scrutinize more closely (not run automatically for all pairs --
   expensive, and meant for spot-checking, same spirit as the Tier 1
   lag validation you already did)

CONFIGURE THE SECTIONS BELOW BEFORE RUNNING.
"""

